  "timeframe": "60-minute to 5-minute",
  "market_context": "On the ES 60-minute chart, price had been respecting a fair value gap with sell-side liquidity (sell stops) resting below. Price dropped on the hourly, swept that sell-side liquidity, and closed back inside, prompting a drill-down to the 5-minute for a long entry.",
  "key_observation": "After the hourly sweep of sell-side liquidity and close back inside, the 5-minute formed a low-high-lower low-higher high breaker structure with an overlapping fair value gap (unicorn model) — a textbook long setup that nonetheless failed.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: On the ES 60-minute chart, identified a respected fair value gap above and sell-side liquidity (sell stops) resting below.",
    "Step 2: Observed the hourly candle drop down, sweep the sell-side liquidity, and close back inside the range — signaling a potential long setup.",
    "Step 3: Dropped to the 5-minute timeframe to refine the entry.",
    "Step 4: On the 5-minute, identified a low-high-lower low-higher high sequence confirming a bullish breaker structure.",
    "Step 5: Marked the breaker block as the series of up-close candles, and noted a fair value gap aligned with it, forming a unicorn model.",
    "Step 6: Planned the entry at the fair value gap, stop below the breaker block, targeting 2R.",
    "Step 7: Price filled the entry but then traded through the stop, resulting in a stop-out."
  ],
  "outcome": "Stopped out — losing trade.",
  "lessons": "Even textbook setups with full top-down alignment (HTF sweep, LTF breaker + FVG unicorn confluence) can fail. Losses are inevitable in trading; consistent execution with defined risk is what matters, not avoiding every losing trade.",
